{"meta":{"authors":[{"id":"6","fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre"}],"title":"","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:14:25 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:14:25 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཡོད་རེད་</span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཞག་</span> (or <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འདུག་</span>), and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཡོད་</span> are directly connected to the past tense form of the main verb. These auxiliaries respectively represent the three evidential moods: assertive, inferential, and egophoric.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁང་པ་གསར་པ་མང་པོ་བརྒྱབ་ཡོད་རེད། </span>&ldquo;Many new houses have been built.&rdquo;</li>\n<li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁང་པ་གསར་པ་མང་པོ་བརྒྱབ་བཞག</span> &ldquo;Look! Many new houses have been built.&rdquo;</li>\n<li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ང་ཇ་བཟོས་ཡོད།</span> &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve made the tea.&rdquo;</li>\n</ul>\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">The range of the perfect forms is presented in the following table:</p>\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><strong>Table: The Perfect Tense Auxiliaries</strong></p>\n<table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"121\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Affirmative</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"121\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Interrogative</p>\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">(without pronouns)</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"121\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Interrogative</p>\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">(with pronouns)</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"121\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Negative</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"121\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\">Negative Interrogative</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"121\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཡོད་</span></p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"121\">\n<p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཡོད་པས་</span></